Constructs the visualization `Tree` from a flat list of `TypedEntry` — one pass renders each entry's snippet text into a leaf `Node`, then delegates to `axis::group` + `grouping::apply_grouping` to bucket leaves under category roots and fill in `children`/`axis`.

The core subtlety is in `insert_leaf`/`root_segment`: entries are merged into nodes by `tree::group_key(entry)`, which strips stroke variants (e.g. `/`-suffixed forms) so that a one-liner and its multi-line counterpart land in the same `Node`. But `one_liner_root` is separately recorded from `root_segment(&entry.stroke)` — the *first* `/`-segment, kept exactly because the one-liner's `U` key visually rides that specific physical stroke, and this must survive even though `group_key` throws the distinction away. Getting this wrong would misplace the one-liner's key-cap rendering in the viz output. Each node is also re-stamped with `entry.terminal` and `desc` on every visit (last-write-wins for `terminal`, first-non-None-wins is not the rule — description is overwritten whenever `desc` is `Some`, so entries sharing a group_key with differing descriptions will silently take the last one's).

Build order matters for reproducibility: `node_order` and `categories` are appended in first-seen (file) order via `HashMap`-backed dedup (`category_index`, and implicitly nodes' first-insert check), so output ordering is stable across runs as long as `typed` iteration order is stable.

`BuildState` bundles five mutable refs purely to dodge clippy's too-many-arguments lint on `insert_entry`/`insert_all` — no other significance.

`build(typed: &[TypedEntry], markers: &[Marker], desc_map: &HashMap<usize, String>) -> Result<Tree, String>` is the sole public entry point; errors are stringified snippet-rendering failures (from `steno::render_snippet`) or `tree::group_key` failures, propagated via `?` with no wrapping context. Depends on sibling modules `axis` (bucketing/grouping algorithm), `comments::{Marker, label_for}` (maps a source line to its enclosing `##` category label), `grouping` (turns nodes into axis inputs and applies the grouping result back), and `tree` (the `Tree`/`Node`/`Category` output types and `group_key`) — changing `group_key`'s semantics or `Node`'s field set requires updating this file in lockstep.